 (8.8), that: \[  rac{\hat\lambda_n}{\sqrt{n}} \overset{d}{ightarrow} \mathcal{N}\left(0,\left( \dfrac{\partial h( oldsymbol	heta_0)}{\partial  oldsymbol	heta&#39;} \mathcal{I}( oldsymbol	heta_0)^{-1}  rac{\partial h&#39;( oldsymbol	heta_0;\mathbf{y})}{\partial  oldsymbol	heta} ight)^{-1}ight). \] Taking the quadratic form of the last equation gives: \[  rac{1}{n}\hat\lambda_n&#39; \dfrac{\partial h(\hat{ oldsymbol	heta}^0_n)}{\partial  oldsymbol	heta&#39;} \mathcal{I}(\hat{ oldsymbol	heta}^0_n)^{-1}  rac{\partial h&#39;(\hat{ oldsymbol	heta}^0_n;\mathbf{y})}{\partial  oldsymbol	heta} \hat\lambda_n \overset{d}{ightarrow} \chi^2(r). \] Using Eq. (8.14), it appears that the left-hand side term of the last equation is \(\xi^{LM}\) as defined in Eq. (3.15). Consistency: see Remark 17.3 in Gouriéroux and Monfort (1995). Proof of Proposition 3.7 Proof. Let us first demonstrate the asymptotic equivalence of \(\xi^{LM}\) and \(\xi^{LR}\). The second-order Taylor expansions of \(\log \mathcal{L}(\hat{ oldsymbol	heta}^0_n,\mathbf{y})\) and \(\log \mathcal{L}(\hat{ oldsymbol	heta}_n,\mathbf{y})\) are: \[ egin{eqnarray*} \log \mathcal{L}(\hat{ oldsymbol	heta}_n,\mathbf{y}) &amp;\approx&amp; \log \mathcal{L}( oldsymbol	heta_0,\mathbf{y}) +  rac{\partial \log \mathcal{L}( oldsymbol	heta_0,\mathbf{y})}{\partial  oldsymbol	heta&#39;}(\hat{ oldsymbol	heta}_n- oldsymbol	heta_0) \ &amp;&amp; -  rac{n}{2} (\hat{ oldsymbol	heta}_n- oldsymbol	heta_0)&#39; \mathcal{I}( oldsymbol	heta_0) (\hat{ oldsymbol	heta}_n- oldsymbol	heta_0)\ \log \mathcal{L}(\hat{ oldsymbol	heta}^0_n,\mathbf{y}) &amp;\approx&amp; \log \mathcal{L}( oldsymbol	heta_0,\mathbf{y}) +  rac{\partial \log \mathcal{L}( oldsymbol	heta_0,\mathbf{y})}{\partial  oldsymbol	heta&#39;}(\hat{ oldsymbol	heta}^0_n- oldsymbol	heta_0) \ &amp;&amp; -  rac{n}{2} (\hat{ oldsymbol	heta}^0_n- oldsymbol	heta_0)&#39; \mathcal{I}( oldsymbol	heta_0) (\hat{ oldsymbol	heta}^0_n- oldsymbol	heta_0). \end{eqnarray*}\] Taking the difference, we obtain: \[ egin{eqnarray*} \xi_n^{LR} &amp;\approx&amp; 2 rac{\partial \log \mathcal{L}( oldsymbol	heta_0,\mathbf{y})}{\partial  oldsymbol	heta&#39;} (\hat{ oldsymbol	heta}_n-\hat{ oldsymbol	heta}^0_n) + n (\hat{ oldsymbol	heta}^0_n- oldsymbol	heta_0)&#39; \mathcal{I}( oldsymbol	heta_0) (\hat{ oldsymbol	heta}^0_n- oldsymbol	heta_0)\ &amp;&amp; - n (\hat{ oldsymbol	heta}_n- oldsymbol	heta_0)&#39; \mathcal{I}( oldsymbol	heta_0) (\hat{ oldsymbol	heta}_n- oldsymbol	heta_0). \end{eqnarray*}\] Using \(\dfrac{1}{\sqrt{n}} rac{\partial \log \mathcal{L}( oldsymbol	heta_0;\mathbf{y})}{\partial  oldsymbol	heta} \approx \mathcal{I}( oldsymbol	heta_0)\sqrt{n}(\hat{ oldsymbol	heta}_n- oldsymbol	heta_0)\) (Eq. (8.11)), we have: \[ egin{eqnarray*} \xi_n^{LR} &amp;\approx&amp; 2n(\hat{ oldsymbol	heta}_n- oldsymbol	heta_0)&#39;\mathcal{I}( oldsymbol	heta_0) (\hat{ oldsymbol	heta}_n-\hat{ oldsymbol	heta}^0_n) + n (\hat{ oldsymbol	heta}^0_n- oldsymbol	heta_0)&#39; \mathcal{I}( oldsymbol	heta_0) (\hat{ oldsymbol	heta}^0_n- oldsymbol	heta_0) \ &amp;&amp; - n (\hat{ oldsymbol	heta}_n- oldsymbol	heta_0)&#39; \mathcal{I}( oldsymbol	heta_0) (\hat{ oldsymbol	heta}_n- oldsymbol	heta_0). \end{eqnarray*}\] In the second of the three terms in the sum, we replace \((\hat{ oldsymbol	heta}^0_n- oldsymbol	heta_0)\) by \((\hat{ oldsymbol	heta}^0_n-\hat{ oldsymbol	heta}_n+\hat{ oldsymbol	heta}_n- oldsymbol	heta_0)\) and we develop the associated product. This leads to: \[ egin{equation} \xi_n^{LR} \approx n (\hat{ oldsymbol	heta}^0_n-\hat{ oldsymbol	heta}_n)&#39; \mathcal{I}( oldsymbol	heta_0)^{-1} (\hat{ oldsymbol	heta}^0_n-\hat{ oldsymbol	heta}_n). 	ag{8.16} \end{equation}\] The difference between Eqs. (8.10) and (8.11) implies: \[  rac{1}{\sqrt{n}} rac{\partial \log \mathcal{L}(\hat{ oldsymbol	heta}^0_n;\mathbf{y})}{\partial  oldsymbol	heta} \approx \mathcal{I}( oldsymbol	heta_0)\sqrt{n}(\hat{ oldsymbol	heta}_n-\hat{ oldsymbol	heta}^0_n), \] which, associated to Eq. @(eq:lr10), gives: \[ \xi_n^{LR} \approx  rac{1}{n}  rac{\partial \log \mathcal{L}(\hat{ oldsymbol	heta}^0_n;\mathbf{y})}{\partial  oldsymbol	heta&#39;} \mathcal{I}( oldsymbol	heta_0)^{-1}  rac{\partial \log \mathcal{L}(\hat{ oldsymbol	heta}^0_n;\mathbf{y})}{\partial  oldsymbol	heta} \approx \xi_n^{LM}. \] Hence \(\xi_n^{LR}\) has the same asymptotic distribution as \(\xi_n^{LM}\). Let’s show that the LR test is consistent. For this, note that: \[ egin{eqnarray*}  rac{\log \mathcal{L}(\hat{ oldsymbol	heta},\mathbf{y}) - \log \mathcal{L}(\hat{ oldsymbol	heta}^0,\mathbf{y})}{n} &amp;=&amp;  rac{1}{n} \sum_{i=1}^n[\log f(y_i;\hat{ oldsymbol	heta}_n) - \log f(y_i;\hat{ oldsymbol	heta}_n^0)]\ &amp;ightarrow&amp; \mathbb{E}_0[\log f(Y; oldsymbol	heta_0) - \log f(Y; oldsymbol	heta_\infty)], \end{eqnarray*}\] where \( oldsymbol	heta_\infty\), the pseudo true value, is such that \(h( oldsymbol	heta_\infty) 
e 0\) (by definition of \(H_1\)). From the Kullback inequality and the asymptotic identifiability of \( oldsymbol	heta_0\), it follows that \(\mathbb{E}_0[\log f(Y; oldsymbol	heta_0) - \log f(Y; oldsymbol	heta_\infty)] &gt;0\). Therefore \(\xi_n^{LR} ightarrow + \infty\) under \(H_1\). Let us now demonstrate the equivalence of \(\xi^{LM} and \xi^{W}\). We have (using Eq. (eq:multiplier)): \[ \xi^{LM}_n =  rac{1}{n}\hat\lambda_n&#39; \dfrac{\partial h(\hat{ oldsymbol	heta}^0_n)}{\partial  oldsymbol	heta&#39;} \mathcal{I}(\hat{ oldsymbol	heta}^0_n)^{-1}  rac{\partial h&#39;(\hat{ oldsymbol	heta}^0_n;\mathbf{y})}{\partial  oldsymbol	heta} \hat\lambda_n. \] Since, under \(H_0\), \(\hat{ oldsymbol	heta}_n^0\approx\hat{ oldsymbol	heta}_n \approx { oldsymbol	heta}_0\), Eq. (8.15) therefore implies that: \[ \xi^{LM} \approx n h(\hat{ oldsymbol	heta}_n)&#39; \left( \dfrac{\partial h(\hat{ oldsymbol	heta}_n)}{\partial  oldsymbol	heta&#39;} \mathcal{I}(\hat{ oldsymbol	heta}_n)^{-1}  rac{\partial h&#39;(\hat{ oldsymbol	heta}_n;\mathbf{y})}{\partial  oldsymbol	heta} ight)^{-1} h(\hat{ oldsymbol	heta}_n) = \xi^{W}, \] which gives the result. 8.5 Additional codes 8.5.1 Simulating GEV distributions The following lines of code have been used to generate Figure 5.2. n.sim &lt;- 4000 par(mfrow=c(1,3), plt=c(.2,.95,.2,.85)) all.rhos &lt;- c(.3,.6,.95) for(j in 1:length(all.rhos)){ theta &lt;- 1/all.rhos[j] v1 &lt;- runif(n.sim) v2 &lt;- runif(n.sim) w &lt;- rep(.000001,n.sim) # solve for f(w) = w*(1 - log(w)/theta) - v2 = 0 for(i in 1:20){ f.i &lt;- w * (1 - log(w)/theta) - v2 f.prime &lt;- 1 - log(w)/theta - 1/theta w &lt;- w - f.i/f.prime } u1 &lt;- exp(v1^(1/theta) * log(w)) u2 &lt;- exp((1-v1)^(1/theta) * log(w)) # Get eps1 and eps2 using the inverse of # the Gumbel distribution&#39;s cdf: eps1 &lt;- -log(-log(u1)) eps2 &lt;- -log(-log(u2)) cbind(cor(eps1,eps2),1-all.rhos[j]^2) plot(eps1,eps2,pch=19,col=&quot;#FF000044&quot;, main=paste(&quot;rho = &quot;,toString(all.rhos[j]),se